author: idespondent
description: Venice wasn‚Äôt built on solid ground... It was built on millions of wooden logs driven deep into the seafloor. Since the year 421 A.D., this floating city has defied both time and engineering logic. While most cities stand on bedrock or concrete, Venice rises on a forest of waterlogged timber. Yes ‚Äî wood. Specifically, alder trees ‚Äî a type that doesn‚Äôt rot underwater. When buried in clay and soaked in salty water, this wood doesn‚Äôt decay ‚Äî it petrifies. Over centuries, it hardens, becoming nearly as tough as stone. A timeless wonder still holding up an entire city. St. Mark‚Äôs Campanile rests on 100,000 wooden piles. The grand Basilica della Salute required over a million. Each pile was hammered in by hand, spaced every half meter, driven up to three meters deep into the seabed. But why build a city on water? In the early 5th century, Italy was under attack by barbarian tribes. Fleeing the invasions, people sought refuge in the muddy, marshy Venetian lagoon. The water was their wall ‚Äî a natural fortress that enemies couldn‚Äôt cross easily.
